Opposite the door to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Sundari Chowk</ENAMEX> stands a stone <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">Krishna</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">temple</ENAMEX> built in the <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">Indian</ENAMEX> shikara style. Beside this <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">temple</ENAMEX> is a huge bell that has no rope (its clapper is swung by hand). To the right of this <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">temple</ENAMEX>, on a tall column, is a gilded image of <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">King</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Yoganarendra Malla</ENAMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="CONTACT_INFO">1684‚Äì1705</ENAMEX>) seated on a throne, unperturbed by a hooded cobra hovering over him. Atop this cobra is a bronze bird like those found on the corners of temple roofs. This <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">king</ENAMEX> once told his <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">people</ENAMEX> that as long as such <ENAMEX TYPE="ANIMAL">birds</ENAMEX> did not fly away, his spirit would remain in the valley.
