<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bhaktapur</ENAMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bhadgaon</ENAMEX>)
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bhaktapur</ENAMEX> lies <NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">16 km</NUMEX> (<NUMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">10 miles</NUMEX>) east of the center of <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Kathmandu</ENAMEX>. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bhaktapur</ENAMEX> means ‚ÄúCity of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Devotees,‚Äù</ENAMEX> and this could today be taken to mean devotion to the old ways, for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bhaktapur</ENAMEX> is even more medieval than <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Old Kathmandu</ENAMEX> or <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Patan</ENAMEX>. Exploring its narrow <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC_DESC">streets</ENAMEX>, you‚Äôll come upon squares filled with pottery drying in the sun and <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">potters</ENAMEX> working at their hand-spun wheels, weavers at their looms, and wood-carvers at work on window frames. <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">Artists</ENAMEX> with the finest of brushes paint the minutely detailed religious paintings called thangkas. These are widely sold, but the best come from <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Bhaktapur</ENAMEX>. Newari <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">families</ENAMEX> also still work the fields that come right to the city‚Äôs edge.
